SIMPLE: osculatory
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Osculatory
<hw>Os"cu*la*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of
or pertaining to kissing; kissing.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>osculatory</xex> ceremony.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or having the
properties of, an osculatrix; capable of osculation; <as>as, a circle
may be <ex>osculatory</ex> with a curve, at a given
point</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Osculatory circle</b></col>. <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <cd>See
<cref>Osculating circle of a curve</cref>, under <er>Circle</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Osculatory plane</b></col> (to a curve of double curvature),
<cd>a plane which passes through three successive points of the
curve.</cd> -- <col><b>Osculatory sphere</b></col><cd> (to a line of
double curvature), a sphere passing through four consecutive points of
the curve.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Osculatory</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Osculatory
<hw>Os"cu*la*to*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
